Die Verlierer bleiben Herausforderer
HARARE: Vor den Präsidentschaftswahlen in diesem Monat war ich überzeugt davon, dass Unregelmäßigkeiten bei den Wahlen ernsthafte Konsequenzen in Simbabwe selbst und im ganzen südlichen Afrika hätten.
Trotz der Schatten von Krieg und Terrorismus rief ich zu fairen und freien Wahlen auf.
Die Menschen von Simbabwe haben sie nicht bekommen.
Stattdessen haben sie Terror erhalten.
In the two years leading up to the presidential elections, the people of Zimbabwe have been victims of intimidation, harassment and threats by the party of Robert Mugabe, the African National Union - Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF), whose programme is state-subsidised terrorism.
The ZANU terrorism is the work of scoundrels among the veterans of Zimbabwe's independence war from two decades ago, government militias and young men, all of whom are supported by the police.
The consequence of intimidation and violence was that my party, the Movement for Democratic Change (MDC), did not reach the electorate in large parts, especially in the rural areas.
Moreover, the government of my opponent, President Mugabe, effectively disempowered hundreds of thousands of voters in the cities, particularly in the capital Harare and in Chitungwiza.
As there were not enough polling stations in total, in my opinion, more than 360,000 people stood in queues in Harare and Chitungwiza alone, without being able to put their ballots into the ballot boxes.
I continue to question the legitimacy of the election results because Mugabe's militias prevented the MDC from deploying election observers at 52% of the rural polling stations.
By the end of the voting, our party had no observers at 6 out of 10 polling stations in the countryside.
This means that Mugabe's supporters were able to enforce their will in these polling stations.
We are currently compiling a comprehensive list of all the polling stations that were controlled solely by ZANU supporters.
In our preliminary investigations, a pattern has already emerged at this early stage: in these polling stations, the majority of votes were cast for Mugabe.
Given the overwhelming evidence, I cannot accept the results of the presidential elections, from which the incumbent president Robert Mugabe emerged as the winner with 56% of the 3 million votes cast.
The official result does not reflect the true will of the people of Zimbabwe and is, in their eyes, illegitimate.
The people of Zimbabwe had their right to choose a president of their own free and democratic choice taken away from them.
The struggle over the election results is a political matter that must be resolved politically.
Food and fuel are in short supply, jobs are being lost, and inflation stands at over 100%.
The people of Zimbabwe were brave and determined and deserve to have this recognized.
Perhaps it is not too late for that.
I am writing this text in sorrow, for Mugabe's regime still ignores the will of the people.
No matter what happens, I will stand by the people as a loyal servant and walk the path with them to the end.
Perhaps the government will arrest me.
I was also arrested for treason before the elections.
In the worst case, they even want to kill me.
But the government will never break the people's will to reclaim their rights and power.
It is up to us to carry out a democratic change.
In the coming days, we will experience moments of fear, but we must not allow despair to overwhelm us.
The political change is unstoppable.
But we must be ready to pay a high price for our freedom.
President Mugabe and his henchmen fear the people, and we have heard that they will do everything to kill the messenger.
If it comes to that, I ask the people of Zimbabwe only to remain strong and to finish what we have started together.
There are many heroes in the people of Zimbabwe - heroes who waited for hours to vote, heroes who were not sent away.
They are the heroes of a new Zimbabwe, whose voice must be heard around the world.
We have walked a very rocky path together to achieve a democratic change in our country.
In the history of humanity, a people have rarely endured such violence and yet have understood how to maintain kindness and exuberance.
I notice that the population of Zimbabwe is impatient.
I understand that.
But in order for there to be a political process, they must be patient and wait.
They cannot just leave these elections as they are, but they must also not fall for Mugabe's provocations and resort to violence.
The people of Zimbabwe want change, in the constitution, in the legal system, legitimate change, and they will achieve it, despite all obstacles.
We know that we are not standing alone.
We know that in all of Africa, elections are rigged.
In most African countries, it seems that irregularities, fraud, and deception during elections are the norm.
In Africa, there is always some crisis related to elections somewhere.
It is sad, but the entire continent is plagued by governments that resort to unfair means when it is time to grant people their right to vote.
But those who want something else can hope.
The struggle in Zimbabwe is not yet over.
There is still time to draw lessons from our experience for Africa and the world.
My people are in the hour of their greatest need.
I pledge not to abandon them.
